{"title_page": "Racek Kobyla of Dvorce", "text_new": "{{Infobox noble|type\n| name              = Racek Kobyla of Dvorce\n| title             = Royal [[Hetman]] of [[Wenceslas IV]]<br/>Burgrave of [[Vy\u0161ehrad]]\n| image             = Racek_Kobyla_z_Dvorce.png\n| caption           = Fictional portrait of Racek from ''[[Kingdom Come: Deliverance]]''\n| alt               = \n| CoA               = [[File:Arms of house Kobyla z Dvorce.png|45px]]\n| more              = no \n| succession        = \n| reign             = \n| reign-type        = \n| predecessor       = \n| successor         = \n| suc-type          = \n| spouse            = Anna of \u00dalibic\n| spouse-type       = \n| issue             = \n| issue-link        = \n| issue-pipe        = \n| full name         = \n| native_name       = \n| styles            = \n| titles            = \n| noble family      = \n| house-type        = \n| father            = \n| mother            = \n| birth_name        =\n| birth_date        =\n| birth_place       = \n| christening_date  = \n| christening_place = \n| death_date        = February 2, 1416\n| death_place       = [[Kutn\u00e1 Hora]]\n| burial_date       = \n| burial_place      = \n| religion          = catholic\n| occupation        = \n| memorials         = \n| website           = <!-- {{{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module            = \n}}\n'''Racek Kobyla of Dvorce''' (also: ''Dvojic'', ''Dvojitz'', or ''Dwoygicz''<ref>{{Cita web|url=http://othes.univie.ac.at/48846/1/50563.pdf|title=Tesi di dottorato di Eva-Katharin Ledel|last=Ledel|first=Eva-Katharin|date=November 15, 2015|format=PDF|p=292}}</ref>) was a [[Bohemian]] landowner, [[hetman]] of [[Wenceslas IV]], and burgrave of [[Vy\u0161ehrad]].\n\n==Biography==\nNot much is known about the early life of Racek. In 1403, he is first mentioned as being the overseer of silver mining at [[St\u0159\u00edbrn\u00e1 Skalice]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cestyapamatky.cz/kolinsko/stribrna-skalice|title=St\u0159\u00edbrn\u00e1 Skalice \u2013 Kol\u00ednsko \u2013 Cesty a pam\u00e1tky|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> In that year, the town was razed by [[Sigismund of Luxembourg]] and Racek initially retreated to [[Talmberk]]. Fleeing the continuing threat of Sigismund, Racek continued to [[Rataje nad S\u00e1zavou]] where he was received by [[Hanu\u0161 of Lip\u00e1]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zavadil |first1=Anton\u00edn J. |title=Kutnohorsko slovem i obrasem - Pr\u00e1ce ve\u0161ker\u00e9ho u\u010ditelstva okresu |url=https://www.cms-kh.cz/sites/default/files/books/zavadil-kutnohorsko_slovem_i_obrazem_2.pdf |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1410, Racek was appointed burgrave of [[Vy\u0161ehrad]] by King Wenceslas. In 1412, he was permitted to build his castle, [[Komorn\u00ed_Hr\u00e1dek#Chateau_Komorn\u00ed_Hr\u00e1dek|Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek]], near modern day [[Chocerady]]. In 1415, Racek was mentioned as a patron of the Chocerady church.<ref name=durdik>{{cite book |last1=Durd\u00edk |first1=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |title=Ilustrovan\u00e1 encyklopedie \u010desk\u00fdch hrad\u016f |date=2002 |publisher=Libri |location=Prague |isbn=80-7277-003-9 |pages=268\u2013269}}</ref> \n\nIn 1416, Racek was sent to [[Kutn\u00e1 Hora]] to collect taxes for the king. He was a known follower of the teachings of [[Jan Hus]], who was proclaimed a heretic. On February 2nd, Racek and 12 of his associates were murdered in a tavern by a mob of miners fueled by religious fervor.<ref name=bohdan>{{cite web |last1=Dobi\u00e1\u0161 |first1=Bohdan |title=P\u0159elou\u010dt\u00ed mu\u010dedn\u00edci |url=http://kostel-evang.webzdarma.cz/husite/husite.htm# |accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote\n|text=\"They seized them in the inn where they were staying, cut their bodies into pieces and threw them out onto the street, where the mob vigorously stomped on their remains and then went in merry song to the home of the preacher to be praised for the act they had been encouraged to commit.\"<ref name=bohdan/><ref name=kcd>{{cite web |title=Codex |url=https://www.kingdomcomerpg.com/ |publisher=Kingdom Come Deliverance |date=2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\nHis castle, along with the villages of Chocerady, {{ill|\u00dadolnice|cs|\u00dadolnice_(Vranov)}}, and [[Vr\u00e1\u017e (Bene\u0161ov District)|Vr\u00e1\u017e]] <small>[[:cs:Vr\u00e1\u017e (Ost\u0159edek)|[cs]]]</small>, were left to his widow, Anna of \u00dalibic. His children were left under the guardianship of the knights Mikul\u00e1\u0161 \u0160ra\u0148ek and Mikul\u00e1\u0161 of Reblic.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=\u0160imek |editor1-first=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |title=Hrady, z\u00e1mky a tvrze v \u010cech\u00e1ch, na Morav\u011b a ve Slezsku |date=1985 |publisher=Nakladatelstv\u00ed Svoboda |location=Prague |pages=202\u2013203}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nRacek features prominently in the video game ''[[Kingdom Come: Deliverance]]'' as Sir Radzig Kobyla.<ref name=kcd/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1416 deaths]]\n[[Category:Medieval Bohemian nobility]]\n[[Category:15th-century Bohemian people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth unknown]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox noble|type\n| name              = Racek Kobyla of Dvorce\n| title             = Royal [[Hetman]] of [[Wenceslas IV]]<br/>Burgrave of [[Vy\u0161ehrad]]\n| image             = Racek_Kobyla_z_Dvorce.png\n| caption           = Fictional portrait of Racek from ''[[Kingdom Come: Deliverance]]''\n| alt               = \n| CoA               = [[File:Arms of house Kobyla z Dvorce.png|45px]]\n| more              = no \n| succession        = \n| reign             = \n| reign-type        = \n| predecessor       = \n| successor         = \n| suc-type          = \n| spouse            = Anna of \u00dalibic\n| spouse-type       = \n| issue             = \n| issue-link        = \n| issue-pipe        = \n| full name         = \n| native_name       = \n| styles            = \n| titles            = \n| noble family      = \n| house-type        = \n| father            = \n| mother            = \n| birth_name        =\n| birth_date        =\n| birth_place       = \n| christening_date  = \n| christening_place = \n| death_date        = February 2, 1416\n| death_place       = [[Kutn\u00e1 Hora]]\n| burial_date       = \n| burial_place      = \n| religion          = catholic\n| occupation        = \n| memorials         = \n| website           = <!-- {{{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module            = \n}}\n'''Racek Kobyla of Dvorce''' (also: ''Dvojic'', ''Dvojitz'', or ''Dwoygicz''<ref>{{Cita web|url=http://othes.univie.ac.at/48846/1/50563.pdf|title=Tesi di dottorato di Eva-Katharin Ledel|last=Ledel|first=Eva-Katharin|date=November 15, 2015|format=PDF|p=292}}</ref>) was a [[Bohemian]] landowner, [[hetman]] of [[Wenceslas IV]], and burgrave of [[Vy\u0161ehrad]].\n\n==Biography==\nNot much is known about the early life of Racek. In 1403, he is first mentioned as being the overseer of silver mining at [[St\u0159\u00edbrn\u00e1 Skalice]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cestyapamatky.cz/kolinsko/stribrna-skalice|title=St\u0159\u00edbrn\u00e1 Skalice \u2013 Kol\u00ednsko \u2013 Cesty a pam\u00e1tky|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> In that year, the town was razed by [[Sigismund of Luxembourg]] and Racek initially retreated to [[Talmberk]]. Fleeing the continuing threat of Sigismund, Racek continued to [[Rataje nad S\u00e1zavou]] where he was received by [[Hanu\u0161 of Lip\u00e1]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zavadil |first1=Anton\u00edn J. |title=Kutnohorsko slovem i obrasem - Pr\u00e1ce ve\u0161ker\u00e9ho u\u010ditelstva okresu |url=https://www.cms-kh.cz/sites/default/files/books/zavadil-kutnohorsko_slovem_i_obrazem_2.pdf |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1410, Racek was appointed burgrave of [[Vy\u0161ehrad]] by King Wenceslas. In 1412, he was permitted to build his castle, [[Komorn\u00ed_Hr\u00e1dek#Komorn\u00ed_Hr\u00e1dek|Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek]], near modern day [[Chocerady]]. In 1415, Racek was mentioned as a patron of the Chocerady church.<ref name=durdik>{{cite book |last1=Durd\u00edk |first1=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |title=Ilustrovan\u00e1 encyklopedie \u010desk\u00fdch hrad\u016f |date=2002 |publisher=Libri |location=Prague |isbn=80-7277-003-9 |pages=268\u2013269}}</ref> \n\nIn 1416, Racek was sent to [[Kutn\u00e1 Hora]] to collect taxes for the king. He was a known follower of the teachings of [[Jan Hus]], who was proclaimed a heretic. On February 2nd, Racek and 12 of his associates were murdered in a tavern by a mob of miners fueled by religious fervor.<ref name=bohdan>{{cite web |last1=Dobi\u00e1\u0161 |first1=Bohdan |title=P\u0159elou\u010dt\u00ed mu\u010dedn\u00edci |url=http://kostel-evang.webzdarma.cz/husite/husite.htm# |accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote\n|text=\"They seized them in the inn where they were staying, cut their bodies into pieces and threw them out onto the street, where the mob vigorously stomped on their remains and then went in merry song to the home of the preacher to be praised for the act they had been encouraged to commit.\"<ref name=bohdan/><ref name=kcd>{{cite web |title=Codex |url=https://www.kingdomcomerpg.com/ |publisher=Kingdom Come Deliverance |date=2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\nHis castle, along with the villages of Chocerady, {{ill|\u00dadolnice|cs|\u00dadolnice_(Vranov)}}, and [[Vr\u00e1\u017e (Bene\u0161ov District)|Vr\u00e1\u017e]] <small>[[:cs:Vr\u00e1\u017e (Ost\u0159edek)|[cs]]]</small>, were left to his widow, Anna of \u00dalibic. His children were left under the guardianship of the knights Mikul\u00e1\u0161 \u0160ra\u0148ek and Mikul\u00e1\u0161 of Reblic.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=\u0160imek |editor1-first=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |title=Hrady, z\u00e1mky a tvrze v \u010cech\u00e1ch, na Morav\u011b a ve Slezsku |date=1985 |publisher=Nakladatelstv\u00ed Svoboda |location=Prague |pages=202\u2013203}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nRacek features prominently in the video game ''[[Kingdom Come: Deliverance]]'' as Sir Radzig Kobyla.<ref name=kcd/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1416 deaths]]\n[[Category:Medieval Bohemian nobility]]\n[[Category:15th-century Bohemian people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth unknown]]\n", "name_user": "Mbdfar", "label": "safe", "comment": "link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Racek_Kobyla_of_Dvorce"}
{"title_page": "Barbara Ruthven", "text_new": "'''Barbara Ruthven''' (died 1625) was a Scottish courtier and favourite of Anne of Denmark, expelled from court after the death of her brother.\n\nBarbabra Ruthven was a daughter of [[William Ruthven, 1st Earl of Gowrie]] and Dorothea Stewart, the oldest daughter of [[Henry Stewart, 1st Lord Methven]] and Janet Stewart, daughter of [[John Stewart, 2nd Earl of Atholl]].\n\nShe was a maid of honour to [[Anne of Denmark]] with her sister Beatrix.<ref>James Balfour Paul, ''Scots Peerage'', vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1907), pp. 266-7.</ref> Beatrix had a prominent role at the christening of [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia|Princess Elizabeth]] in November 1596, for which the queen bought her a gown of figured black velvet with white sleeves and a yellow skirt.<ref>Michael Pearce, 'Anna of Denmark: Fashioning a Danish Court in Scotland', ''The Court Historian'', 24:2 (2019) p. 149.</ref> Christene Ruthven, another gentlewoman listed in the queen's household may have been another sister.\n\nJames Hudson noted Barbara having a secret conversation with the Scottish ambassador [[Robert Crichton, 8th Lord Crichton of Sanquhar]] in May 1597.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1952), p. 526.</ref>\n\nThe [[John Ruthven, 3rd Earl of Gowrie|Earl of Gowrie]] and one of his brothers were killed in a struggle with [[James VI of Scotland]] on 5 August 1600 at Gowrie House in Perth. After this, his sisters were protected by Anne of Denmark even though James wished them to be excluded from his presence, and had ordered them to be 'thrust out' of [[Falkland Palace]]. On 1 November 1600 Dorothea Stewart, who was staying at [[Dirleton Castle]], hoped that the king could be persuaded to support her daughters, \"quhais estait is verie desolait\" and she could not help them herself.<ref>''HMC 9th Report and Appendix, Elphinstone'' (London, 1884), p. 196.</ref>\n\nTwo younger brothers went to [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] and lived in hiding for a month, until the Marshall of the town [[John Carey, 3rd Baron Hunsdon|Sir John Carey]] helped them travel to Durham and Cambridge.<ref>''Border Papers'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1894), p. 684.</ref> [[Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Sir Robert Cecil]], who was in the confidence of Anne of Denmark, helped Barbara travel to London.\n\nSir Robert Cecil understood that [[Anne of Denmark]] and Queen Elizabeth were agreed that Barbara should come to London in August 1602. In September [[Roger Aston]] told James VI that Beatrix Ruthven was in England.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 part 2 (Edinburgh, 1969), pp. 1033, 1049.</ref> However, an agent of Elizabeth told James that she would not have any dealings with the Gowrie sisters.<ref>John Bruce, ''Letters of Queen Elizabeth and James'' (London, 1849), pp. 146-7.</ref> Cecil wrote a letter, probably to the [[Patrick Gray, 6th Lord Gray|Master of Gray]], explaining the delicate and flammable situation of Elizabeth receiving letters asking for the relief of 'that house which is touched with the infamy of attempting the king's blood'.<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'' vol. 14 (London, 10923), pp. 247-9.</ref>\n\nBarbara was in London when on 25 December 1602 her sister Beatrix Ruthven was smuggled into the apartments of Anne of Denmark posing as a gentlewoman servant to [[Claud Hamilton, 1st Lord Paisley|Lady Paisley]] or [[William Douglas, 10th Earl of Angus|Lady Angus]], at the queen's request.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 part 2 (Edinburgh, 1969), pp. 1092, 1096.</ref> There was a rumour in February 1603 that Barbara Ruthven had returned to Scotland by boat.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 part 2 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 1107.</ref>\n\n[[Roger Aston]] discussed with Anne of Denmark how her support for the Gowrie brothers and sisters and a suspected plot against King James may have dented her reputation in England. Early in 1603 Barbara came to London again from Cambridge (where her brothers were) and had new clothes made for her. James Hudson wrote to Sir Robert Cecil saying there were rumours she came to join Elizabeth's household or seek favours for her brothers.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 part 2 (Edinburgh, 1969), pp. 1110, 1126-7.</ref>\n\nRuthven's appearance seemed striking and her speech foreign to the lawyer [[John Manningham]] who wrote, 'I sawe this afternoone a Scottishe Lady at Mr. Fleetes in Loathebury; shee was sister to Earl Gowre, a gallant tall gentlewoman, somewhat long visage, a lisping fumbling language. Peter Saltingstone came to visit hir' and 'was with the Lady Barbara, Shee saith the King will not swear, but he will curse and ban at hunting, and wish the divel goe with them all'.<ref>John Bruce, ''Diary of John Manningham'' (London, 1868), p. 156, 168. 'Saltingstone' is probably Peter Saltonstall of the Middle Temple who visited Scotland with [[Benjamin Rudyerd]] in October 1601, and perhaps a son of [[Richard Saltonstall (mayor)|Richard Saltonstall]], [[Lord Mayor of London]].</ref>\n\nIn May 1603 Cecil organised an exchequer payment to his steward Roger Houghton for \u00a3300 spent on Barbara Ruthven's relief, and she was later given a yearly pension of \u00a3200.<ref>Frederick Devon, ''Issues of the Exchequer during the Reign of James I'' (London, 1836), p. 5, 36.</ref> In Scotland early in 1604, the Earl of Mar heard an unlikely rumour that Cecil would marry Barbara Ruthven.<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'' (London, 1933), pp. 29-30.</ref> She was granted a royal pension of \u00a3200 yearly.<ref>\"HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 20 (London, 1968), p. 305.</ref>\n\nIn 1622 Barbara Ruthven was the administrator of the will of [[Elizabeth Brydges|Sir John Kennedy]], appointed because his daughter Dorothy was too young to be executrix.<ref>J. & G. Matthews, ''Abstracts of Probates and Sentences in the Prerogative Court of Canterbury, 1620-24'' (London, 1911), p. 183: 'Will of Sir John Kennedy of Barnes, Surrey', 8 April 1622, TNA PROB 11/139/311.</ref>\n\nBarbara was buried at Greenwich on 29 December 1625.<ref>Daniel Lysons, ''The Environs of London: Counties of Herts, Essex & Kent'', vol. 4 (London, 1796), p. 474.</ref>\n\nBeatrix married Sir James Home of Coldenknowes and died in Scotland. Their son was [[James Home, 3rd Earl of Home]].\n\nThere has been some confusion with \"Lady Ruthin\", [[Elizabeth Grey, Countess of Kent|Elizabeth Talbot Grey, Countess of Kent]], who became first lady of the bedchamber to Anne of Denmark in 1617.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruthven, Barbara}}\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:Scottish ladies-in-waiting]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:Women of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:1625 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n", "text_old": "'''Barbara Ruthven''' (died 1625) Scottish courtier and favourite of Anne of Denmark, expelled from court after the death of her brother.\n\nBarbabra Ruthven was a daughter of [[William Ruthven, 1st Earl of Gowrie]] and Dorothea Stewart, the oldest daughter of [[Henry Stewart, 1st Lord Methven]] and Janet Stewart, daughter of [[John Stewart, 2nd Earl of Atholl]].\n\nShe was a maid of honour to [[Anne of Denmark]] with her sister Beatrix.<ref>James Balfour Paul, ''Scots Peerage'', vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1907), pp. 266-7.</ref> Beatrix had a prominent role at the christening of [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia|Princess Elizabeth]] in November 1596, for which the queen bought her a gown of figured black velvet with white sleeves and a yellow skirt.<ref>Michael Pearce, 'Anna of Denmark: Fashioning a Danish Court in Scotland', ''The Court Historian'', 24:2 (2019) p. 149.</ref> Christene Ruthven, another gentlewoman listed in the queen's household may have been another sister.\n\nJames Hudson noted Barbara having a secret conversation with the Scottish ambassador [[Robert Crichton, 8th Lord Crichton of Sanquhar]] in May 1597.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1952), p. 526.</ref>\n\nThe [[John Ruthven, 3rd Earl of Gowrie|Earl of Gowrie]] and one of his brothers were killed in a struggle with [[James VI of Scotland]] on 5 August 1600 at Gowrie House in Perth. After this, his sisters were protected by Anne of Denmark even though James wished them to be excluded from his presence, and had ordered them to be 'thrust out' of [[Falkland Palace]]. On 1 November 1600 Dorothea Stewart, who was staying at [[Dirleton Castle]], hoped that the king could be persuaded to support her daughters, \"quhais estait is verie desolait\" and she could not help them herself.<ref>''HMC 9th Report and Appendix, Elphinstone'' (London, 1884), p. 196.</ref>\n\nTwo younger brothers went to [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] and lived in hiding for a month, until the Marshall of the town [[John Carey, 3rd Baron Hunsdon|Sir John Carey]] helped them travel to Durham and Cambridge.<ref>''Border Papers'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1894), p. 684.</ref> [[Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Sir Robert Cecil]], who was in the confidence of Anne of Denmark, helped Barbara travel to London.\n\nSir Robert Cecil understood that [[Anne of Denmark]] and Queen Elizabeth were agreed that Barbara should come to London in August 1602. In September [[Roger Aston]] told James VI that Beatrix Ruthven was in England.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 part 2 (Edinburgh, 1969), pp. 1033, 1049.</ref> However, an agent of Elizabeth told James that she would not have any dealings with the Gowrie sisters.<ref>John Bruce, ''Letters of Queen Elizabeth and James'' (London, 1849), pp. 146-7.</ref> Cecil wrote a letter, probably to the [[Patrick Gray, 6th Lord Gray|Master of Gray]], explaining the delicate and flammable situation of Elizabeth receiving letters asking for the relief of 'that house which is touched with the infamy of attempting the king's blood'.<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'' vol. 14 (London, 10923), pp. 247-9.</ref>\n\nBarbara was in London when on 25 December 1602 her sister Beatrix Ruthven was smuggled into the apartments of Anne of Denmark posing as a gentlewoman servant to [[Claud Hamilton, 1st Lord Paisley|Lady Paisley]] or [[William Douglas, 10th Earl of Angus|Lady Angus]], at the queen's request.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 part 2 (Edinburgh, 1969), pp. 1092, 1096.</ref> There was a rumour in February 1603 that Barbara Ruthven had returned to Scotland by boat.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 part 2 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 1107.</ref>\n\n[[Roger Aston]] discussed with Anne of Denmark how her support for the Gowrie brothers and sisters and a suspected plot against King James may have dented her reputation in England. Early in 1603 Barbara came to London again from Cambridge (where her brothers were) and had new clothes made for her. James Hudson wrote to Sir Robert Cecil saying there were rumours she came to join Elizabeth's household or seek favours for her brothers.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 part 2 (Edinburgh, 1969), pp. 1110, 1126-7.</ref>\n\nRuthven's appearance seemed striking and her speech foreign to the lawyer [[John Manningham]] who wrote, 'I sawe this afternoone a Scottishe Lady at Mr. Fleetes in Loathebury; shee was sister to Earl Gowre, a gallant tall gentlewoman, somewhat long visage, a lisping fumbling language. Peter Saltingstone came to visit hir' and 'was with the Lady Barbara, Shee saith the King will not swear, but he will curse and ban at hunting, and wish the divel goe with them all'.<ref>John Bruce, ''Diary of John Manningham'' (London, 1868), p. 156, 168. 'Saltingstone' is probably Peter Saltonstall of the Middle Temple who visited Scotland with [[Benjamin Rudyerd]] in October 1601, and perhaps a son of [[Richard Saltonstall (mayor)|Richard Saltonstall]], [[Lord Mayor of London]].</ref>\n\nIn May 1603 Cecil organised an exchequer payment to his steward Roger Houghton for \u00a3300 spent on Barbara Ruthven's relief, and she was later given a yearly pension of \u00a3200.<ref>Frederick Devon, ''Issues of the Exchequer during the Reign of James I'' (London, 1836), p. 5, 36.</ref> In Scotland early in 1604, the Earl of Mar heard an unlikely rumour that Cecil would marry Barbara Ruthven.<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'' (London, 1933), pp. 29-30.</ref> She was granted a royal pension of \u00a3200 yearly.<ref>\"HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 20 (London, 1968), p. 305.</ref>\n\nIn 1622 Barbara Ruthven was the administrator of the will of [[Elizabeth Brydges|Sir John Kennedy]], appointed because his daughter Dorothy was too young to be executrix.<ref>J. & G. Matthews, ''Abstracts of Probates and Sentences in the Prerogative Court of Canterbury, 1620-24'' (London, 1911), p. 183: 'Will of Sir John Kennedy of Barnes, Surrey', 8 April 1622, TNA PROB 11/139/311.</ref>\n\nBarbara was buried at Greenwich on 29 December 1625.<ref>Daniel Lysons, ''The Environs of London: Counties of Herts, Essex & Kent'', vol. 4 (London, 1796), p. 474.</ref>\n\nBeatrix married Sir James Home of Coldenknowes and died in Scotland. Their son was [[James Home, 3rd Earl of Home]].\n\nThere has been some confusion with \"Lady Ruthin\", [[Elizabeth Grey, Countess of Kent|Elizabeth Talbot Grey, Countess of Kent]], who became first lady of the bedchamber to Anne of Denmark in 1617.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruthven, Barbara}}\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:Scottish ladies-in-waiting]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:Women of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:1625 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n", "name_user": "Horsesamurai", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barbara_Ruthven"}
{"title_page": "Godavari-Krishna mangroves", "text_new": "{{short description|A mangrove ecoregion of India's eastern coast}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Krishna godavari delta region.png|thumb|300px|right|[[Krishna River]] Delta (lower left) and [[Godavari River]] delta (upper right) imagery showing the green mangrove region.]]\n[[File:Mangroves W IMG 6896.jpg|thumb|300px|Mangroves in Krishna Delta region]]\n[[File:Excoecaria agallocha (Blind Your Eye) W IMG 6949.jpg|thumb|300px|''[[Excoecaria agallocha]]'' trees at Krishna Delta]]\nThe '''Godavari-Krishna mangroves''' are a [[mangrove]] [[ecoregion]] of [[India]]'s eastern coast.\n\n==Location and description==\nThe ecoregion covers an area of {{convert|7,000|km2|sqmi|sp=us}}, in discontinuous enclaves extending from the state of [[Orissa, India|Orissa]] in the north to [[Tamil Nadu]] in the south. The largest mangrove community in the ecoregion lies in the [[river delta|delta]] of the [[Godavari River|Godavari]] and [[Krishna River|Krishna]] rivers in [[Andhra Pradesh]]; other mangrove communities can be found at [[Point Calimere]] in [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Pulicat Lake]] in [[Andhra Pradesh]] and [[Tamil Nadu]], and the [[Bhitarkanika Mangroves]] and [[Chilika Lake]] in [[Orissa, India|Orissa]].<ref>http://www.worldwildlife.org/wildworld/profiles/terrestrial/im/im1401_full.html Godavari-Krishna mangroves at the World Wildlife Fund</ref>\n\n==Flora==\nThe predominant mangroves are all of the species include ''[[Avicennia marina]]'', ''[[Suaeda]]'' spp., ''[[Rhizophora]]'' spp., and ''[[Bruguiera]]'' spp. These have a thick canopy and an undergrowth of climbing plants and shrubs.\n\n==Fauna==\nMangroves are an important coastal habitat for much wildlife such as the [[saltwater crocodile]]s who shelter among the roots and feed of the fish and other seafood in this warm mixture of fresh and seawater. These mangroves are home to  many insects, [[mollusc]]s, shrimp, crabs and fish as well as 140 bird species, including the threatened [[lesser florican]] (''Eupodotis indica''), best known for the male birds' leaping breeding displays, and large communities of aquatic birds such as [[egret]]s, [[flamingo]]es (''Phoenicoptreus'' spp.), [[spot-billed pelican]]s (''Pelecanus philippensis''), [[spoonbill]]s (''Platalea'' spp.), and [[painted stork]]s (''Mycteria leucocephala'').\n\n==Threats and preservation==\nMangroves are vulnerable to coastal development including prawn farming, other agriculture that diverts fresh water from reaching the coast and seaside urbanisation. Most mangroves on the east coast of India have been cleared and while 14% of the ecoregion is under protection in [[Point Calimere Wildlife and Bird Sanctuary]], [[Pulicat Lake Bird Sanctuary]] and the [[Bhitarkanika National Park]] even those areas are not secure.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ecoregions of India]]\n[[Category:Mangrove ecoregions]]\n[[Category:Forests of India]]\n[[Category:Godavari River]]\n[[Category:Krishna River]]\n[[Category:Flora of India (region)|*]]\n[[Category:Indomalayan ecoregions]]\n[[Category:Western Indo-Pacific]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A mangrove ecoregion of India's eastern coast}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Krishna godavari delta region.png|thumb|300px|right|[[Krishna River]] Delta (lower left) and [[Godavari River]] delta (upper right) imagery showing the green mangrove region.]]\n[[File:Mangroves W IMG 6896.jpg|thumb|300px|Mangroves in Krishna Delta region]]\n[[File:Excoecaria agallocha (Blind Your Eye) W IMG 6949.jpg|thumb|300px|''[[Excoecaria agallocha]]'' trees at Krishna Delta]]\nThe '''Godavari-Krishna mangroves''' are a [[mangrove]] [[ecoregion]] of [[India]]'s eastern coast.\n\n==Location and description==\nThe ecoregion covers an area of {{convert|7,000|km2|sqmi|sp=us}}, in discontinuous enclaves extending from the state of [[Orissa, India|Orissa]] in the north to [[Tamil Nadu]] in the south. The largest mangrove community in the ecoregion lies in the [[river delta|delta]] of the [[Godavari River|Godavari]] and [[Krishna River|Krishna]] rivers in [[Andhra Pradesh]]; other mangrove communities can be found at [[Point Calimere]] in [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Pulicat Lake]] in [[Andhra Pradesh]] and [[Tamil Nadu]], and the [[Bhitarkanika Mangroves]] and [[Chilika Lake]] in [[Orissa, India|Orissa]].<ref>http://www.worldwildlife.org/wildworld/profiles/terrestrial/im/im1401_full.html Godavari-Krishna mangroves at the World Wildlife Fund</ref>\n\n==Flora==\nThe predominant mangroves are all of the species include ''[[Avicennia marina]]'', ''[[Suaeda]]'' spp., ''[[Rhizophora]]'' spp., and ''[[Bruguiera]]'' spp. These have a thick canopy and an undergrowth of climbing plants and shrubs.\n\n==Fauna==\nMangroves are an important coastal habitat for much wildlife such as the [[saltwater crocodile]]s who shelter among the roots and feed of the fish and other seafood in this warm mixture of fresh and seawater. These mangroves are home to  many insects, [[mollusc]]s, shrimp, crabs and fish as well as 140 bird species, including the threatened [[lesser florican]] (''Eupodotis indica''), best known for the male birds' leaping breeding displays, and large communities of aquatic birds such as [[egret]]s, [[flamingo]]es (''Phoenicoptreus'' spp.), [[spot-billed pelican]]s (''Pelecanus philippensis''), [[spoonbill]]s (''Platalea'' spp.), and [[painted stork]]s (''Mycteria leucocephala'').\n\n==Threats and preservation==\nMangroves are vulnerable to coastal development including prawn farming, other agriculture that diverts fresh water from reaching the coast and seaside urbanisation. Most mangroves on the east coast of India have been cleared and while 14% of the ecoregion is under protection in [[Point Calimere Wildlife and Bird Sanctuary]], [[Pulicat Lake Bird Sanctuary]] and the [[Bhitarkanika National Park]] even those areas are not secure.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ecoregions of India]]\n[[Category:Mangrove ecoregions]]\n[[Category:Forests of India]]\n[[Category:Godavari River]]\n[[Category:Krishna River]]\n[[Category:Flora of India|*]]\n[[Category:Indomalayan ecoregions]]\n[[Category:Western Indo-Pacific]]\n", "name_user": "Declangi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Category:Flora of India (region) - WGSRPD category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Godavari-Krishna_mangroves"}
{"title_page": "Geralt of Rivia", "text_new": "{{Infobox character\n| name        = Geraldo of Libya\n| image       = Geralt of Rivia Witcher.png\n| image_size  = 250px\n| caption     = Henry Cavill as Geralt in the television series ''The Witcher'' (2019\u2013present)\n| series      = [[The Witcher]]\n| first       = {{Plainlist|\n* '''Literature''':\n* [[The Last Wish (book)#\"The Witcher\"|\"The Witcher\"]] (1986)\n* '''Film''':\n* [[The Hexer (film)|''The Hexer'']] (2001)\n* '''Television''':\n* \"Childhood\" (2002) <br> ([[The Hexer (TV series)|''The Hexer'']])\n* \"The End's Beginning\" (2019) (''[[The Witcher (TV series)|The Witcher]]'')\n}}\n| firstgame = ''[[The Witcher (video game)|The Witcher]]'' (2007)\n| last        = {{Plainlist|\n* '''Literature''':\n* ''[[Season of Storms]]'' (2013)\n* '''Film''':\n* ''The Hexer'' (2001)\n* '''Television''':\n* \"Ciri\" (2002) <br> (''The Hexer'')\n}}\n| creator     = [[Andrzej Sapkowski]]\n| portrayer   = [[Micha\u0142 \u017bebrowski]]<br />(''The Hexer'' film and TV series)<br />[[Henry Cavill]]<br />(''The Witcher'' TV series)\n| voice = '''Polish''':<br>[[Jacek Rozenek]]<br>'''English''':<br />[[Doug Cockle]]<br />'''Japanese''':<br>[[Kazuhiro Yamaji]]\n| aliases       = White Wolf<br />Gwynbleidd<br />Butcher of Blaviken<br />Ravix of Fourhorn<br />Butcher of White Orchard<br/>\n| gender      = Male\n| species = Witcher\n| occupation  = Monster slayer\n| family = Visenna (mother)\n| children = Ciri (adopted daughter)\n| significant_others = Yennefer of Vengerberg (lover)<br />Triss Merigold (lover)<br />Fringilla Vigo (lover)\n}}\n\n'''Geralt of Rivia''' ({{lang-pl|Geralt z Rivii}}) is a fictional character and the [[protagonist]] of ''[[The Witcher]]'' series of short stories and novels by Polish writer [[Andrzej Sapkowski]]. Geralt, one of the few remaining witchers on the Continent, is a traveling monster slayer for hire, mutated and trained from an early age to slay deadly beasts.\n\nGeralt is portrayed by [[Micha\u0142 \u017bebrowski]] in [[The Hexer (film)|''The Hexer'' film]] and [[The Hexer (TV series)|TV series]], and is portrayed by [[Henry Cavill]] in the [[The Witcher (TV series)|Netflix television adaptation.]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/henry-cavill-the-witcher-netflix-series-1202925521/ |title=Henry Cavill to Star in \u2018Witcher\u2019 Series at Netflix |last=Otterson |first=Joe |date=4 September 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |access-date=5 September 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Fictional biography==\n<!--This is the original character's biography from books-->\nGeralt is a [[The Witcher|witcher]]. Shortly after being born, Geralt's mother, Visenna, gave him away to undergo training and, eventually, become a witcher at Kaer Morhen - the stronghold of the witchers. Geralt survived mutations during the Trial of the Grasses, thanks to which he gained various witcher traits: high resistance to injury, poison and disease, slowed ageing, but also infertility. He resisted the \"changes\" brought on by the Trial of Grasses better than most, which encouraged his makers to perform even more dangerous experimental procedures on him, making him lose all body pigmentation. Because of his pale skin and white hair, he is also known in the Elder Speech as \"Gwynbleidd\" (close to the Welsh translation \"Blaidd Gwyn\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geek.com/television/heres-what-you-should-know-about-geralt-of-rivia-in-netflixs-the-witcher-1814551/|title=Here\u2019s What You Should Know About Geralt of Rivia in Netflix\u2019s \u2018The Witcher\u2019|last=Gemmill|first=Allie|date=December 21, 2019|website=Geek|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref>), the White Wolf. From the arduous training of Witchers, he became a master swordfighter and learnt how to use the Signs, simple spells used by the witchers.\n\nDespite his name, Geralt does not come from [[The Witcher#Setting|Rivia]] (although he learned how to mimic a Rivian [[Accent (sociolinguistics)|accent]] and is later knighted for services to the queen of Rivia): young witchers were encouraged to make up surnames for themselves by master Vesemir, to make their names sound more trustworthy. He once claimed that his first choice was Geralt Roger Eric du Haute-Bellegarde, but this was dismissed by Vesemir as silly and pretentious.\n\nAfter completing his witcher training, he received his Wolf medallion (the symbol of Kaer Morhen) and embarked into the world on his horse called ''P\u0142otka'' (literally, \"[[Common roach|Roach]]\" with a diminutive suffix, more accurately \"Roachie\" in English; he gave the same name to every horse he owned) to become a monster slayer for hire.\n\n{{Quote|text=I looked for the words \"Witcher urgently needed\". And then there'd be a sacred site, a dungeon, necropolis or ruins, forest ravine or grotto hidden in the mountains, full of bones and stinking carcasses. Some creatures which lived to kill, out of hunger, for pleasure, or invoked by some sick will. A manticore, wyvern, fogler, aeschna, ilyocoris, chimera, leshy, vampire, ghoul, graveir, were-wolf, giant scorpion, striga, black annis, kikimora, vypper... so many I've killed.|character=Geralt|author=[[Andrzej Sapkowski]]|title=''[[The Last Wish (book)|The Last Wish]]''|source=\"The Voice of Reason 4\"}}\n\nEven though Geralt did not believe in destiny, he unknowingly demanded the unborn child of princess Pavetta and her husband Duny as a reward for his services by invoking \"the Law of Surprise\". The child turned out to be a girl, [[Ciri (character)|Cirilla]], commonly known as Ciri; since then the two are linked to each other. At first, Geralt did not take her because women cannot become witchers. However, fate caused Geralt and Ciri to cross their paths thrice, with him claiming her for a second time when he invokes the Law of Surprise on a traveling merchant he saves from monsters during a random encounter; and after the death of her grandmother, Queen Calanthe of Cintra, Geralt ends up taking the girl into his care, training and loving her as his own daughter. \n\nFollowing the short stories, the novels unfold as Geralt is pulled into a whirlwind of events in his attempts to protect Ciri from those who would do her harm, becoming reluctantly embroiled in the political contentions of monarchs and emperors.\n\n==Literary analysis and reception ==\nGeralt is described as being emblematic of Polish popular culture's spirit of \"[[neo-liberal]] anti-politics\" in the 1990s.<ref name=\"Apor2008\">{{cite book|last=Apor|first=P\u00e9ter|title=Past for the eyes: East European representations of communism in cinema and museums after 1989|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SO8LAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=28 May 2011|year=2008|publisher=Central European University Press|isbn=9789639776050|page=198}}</ref> He is a professional, carrying out his duties and unwilling to become involved in the \"petty quarrels\" of the contemporary politics.<ref name=\"Apor2008\"/> [[Marek Oramus]] compared Geralt to [[Raymond Chandler]]'s signature character [[Philip Marlowe]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Oramus |first=Marek |author-link=Marek Oramus |date=2 September 2000 |title=Only the right image of a witcher |trans-title=Jedynie s\u0142uszny wizerunek wied\u017amina |url=https://archiwum.polityka.pl/art/jedynie-sluszny-wizerunek-wiedzmina,365834.html |language=Polish |work=[[Polityka]] |location=[[Poland]] |access-date=30 May 2011 |pages=52\u201354}}</ref> In 2018, [[GamesRadar]] ranked him as the 6th best hero in video game history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/heroes-in-video-games/3/ |title=The best heroes in video games |last= |first= |date=28 February 2018 |website=[[GamesRadar+]] |publisher=[[Future plc|Future Publishing]] |access-date=31 October 2018 |quote=}}</ref> In 2018, Geralt was included in [[Tom's Guide]] Top 25 Best Video Game Characters of All Time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tomsguide.com/us/pictures-story/1544-best-video-game-characters-of-all-time.html|title=The 25 Best Video Game Characters of All Time|last=July 2018|first=Tom's Guide Staff 07|website=Tom's Guide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==In other media==\n=== Film ===\n[[Micha\u0142 \u017bebrowski]] portrays Geralt in the Polish-language adaptation movie ''[[The Hexer (film)|The Hexer]]''.\n\n===Television===\n* [[Micha\u0142 \u017bebrowski]] portrays Geralt in the polish adaptation series ''[[The Hexer (TV series)|The Hexer]]''.\n* [[Henry Cavill]] portrays Geralt in the [[Netflix]] [[The Witcher (TV series)|adaptation of the books]], the first season of which was released in 2019.<ref name=\"directors\">{{cite web | url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/netflixs-the-witcher-casts-pivotal-roles-of-ciri-yennefer | title=Netflix\u2019S The Witcher casts pivotal roles of Ciri & Yennefer | date=10 October 2018 | publisher=Netflix | accessdate=16 January 2019 }}</ref> Sapkowski served as a creative consultant on the project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/witcher-saga-tv-series-adaptation-ordered-at-netflix-1004558|title='The Witcher' Saga TV Series Adaptation Ordered at Netflix|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Geralt of Rivia.png|thumb|Geralt as he appears in ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]'' (2015)]] -->[[File:W3 SS Geralt.png|thumb|208x208px|Geralt in ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]'']]\nGeralt's adventures continues in a non-canonical version by CD Projekt Red's video game trilogy (''[[The Witcher (video game)|The Witcher]]'', ''[[The Witcher 2: Assassins of Kings]]'' and ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]''), where he is still alive after being killed by a mob during an anti non-human riot at the end of the Witcher novel saga and his body was taken in a boat by his daughter Ciri to [[Avalon]].\n\nSapkowski stated that the games are a work of art of their own and that they cannot be considered either an \"alternative version\", or a sequel, \"because this can only be told by Geralt's creator. A certain Andrzej Sapkowski.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-11-06-ever-wondered-what-the-author-of-the-witcher-books-thinks-about-the-games|title=Ever wondered what the author of The Witcher books thinks about the games?|last=Purchese|first=Robert|date=7 November 2012|work=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nGeralt, voiced by [[Doug Cockle]], appeared as a guest character in the 2018 game ''[[Soulcalibur VI]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.cdprojektred.com/news/play-as-geralt-of-rivia-in-soulcalibur-vi/ |title=Play as Geralt of Rivia in SOULCALIBUR VI! |last= |first= |date=15 March 2018 |website=[[CD Projekt|CD Projekt Red]] |publisher=[[CD Projekt]] |access-date=19 March 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nGeralt also appeared in special content for ''[[Monster Hunter: World]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2019/02/08/monster-hunter-world-the-witcher-ciri-geralt/|title=Monster Hunter World x The Witcher contracts earn you Geralt and Ciri armor and weapon sets|last=Nunneley|first=Stephany|date=February 8, 2019|work=[[VG247]]|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> and ''[[Daemon X Machina]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dualshockers.com/daemon-x-machina-witcher-3-geralt-ciri-dlc/|title=Daemon X Machina Meets The Witcher 3 With New Geralt and Ciri DLC|date=2019-12-05|website=DualShockers|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Novels}}\n*[[Reynevan]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Witcher series}}\n{{Soul series}}\n\n[[Category:The Witcher]]\n[[Category:Characters in fantasy novel series]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video game characters]]\n[[Category:Fantasy film characters]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1986]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who use magic]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with accelerated healing]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with albinism]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with superhuman strength]]\n[[Category:Fictional knights]]\n[[Category:Fictional mutants]]\n[[Category:Fictional monster hunters]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Soulcalibur series guest characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox character\n| name        = Geralt of Rivia\n| image       = Geralt of Rivia Witcher.png\n| image_size  = 250px\n| caption     = Henry Cavill as Geralt in the television series ''The Witcher'' (2019\u2013present)\n| series      = [[The Witcher]]\n| first       = {{Plainlist|\n* '''Literature''':\n* [[The Last Wish (book)#\"The Witcher\"|\"The Witcher\"]] (1986)\n* '''Film''':\n* [[The Hexer (film)|''The Hexer'']] (2001)\n* '''Television''':\n* \"Childhood\" (2002) <br> ([[The Hexer (TV series)|''The Hexer'']])\n* \"The End's Beginning\" (2019) (''[[The Witcher (TV series)|The Witcher]]'')\n}}\n| firstgame = ''[[The Witcher (video game)|The Witcher]]'' (2007)\n| last        = {{Plainlist|\n* '''Literature''':\n* ''[[Season of Storms]]'' (2013)\n* '''Film''':\n* ''The Hexer'' (2001)\n* '''Television''':\n* \"Ciri\" (2002) <br> (''The Hexer'')\n}}\n| creator     = [[Andrzej Sapkowski]]\n| portrayer   = [[Micha\u0142 \u017bebrowski]]<br />(''The Hexer'' film and TV series)<br />[[Henry Cavill]]<br />(''The Witcher'' TV series)\n| voice = '''Polish''':<br>[[Jacek Rozenek]]<br>'''English''':<br />[[Doug Cockle]]<br />'''Japanese''':<br>[[Kazuhiro Yamaji]]\n| aliases       = White Wolf<br />Gwynbleidd<br />Butcher of Blaviken<br />Ravix of Fourhorn<br />Butcher of White Orchard<br/>\n| gender      = Male\n| species = Witcher\n| occupation  = Monster slayer\n| family = Visenna (mother)\n| children = Ciri (adopted daughter)\n| significant_others = Yennefer of Vengerberg (lover)<br />Triss Merigold (lover)<br />Fringilla Vigo (lover)\n}}\n\n'''Geralt of Rivia''' ({{lang-pl|Geralt z Rivii}}) is a fictional character and the [[protagonist]] of ''[[The Witcher]]'' series of short stories and novels by Polish writer [[Andrzej Sapkowski]]. Geralt, one of the few remaining witchers on the Continent, is a traveling monster slayer for hire, mutated and trained from an early age to slay deadly beasts.\n\nGeralt is portrayed by [[Micha\u0142 \u017bebrowski]] in [[The Hexer (film)|''The Hexer'' film]] and [[The Hexer (TV series)|TV series]], and is portrayed by [[Henry Cavill]] in the [[The Witcher (TV series)|Netflix television adaptation.]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/henry-cavill-the-witcher-netflix-series-1202925521/ |title=Henry Cavill to Star in \u2018Witcher\u2019 Series at Netflix |last=Otterson |first=Joe |date=4 September 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |access-date=5 September 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Fictional biography==\n<!--This is the original character's biography from books-->\nGeralt is a [[The Witcher|witcher]]. Shortly after being born, Geralt's mother, Visenna, gave him away to undergo training and, eventually, become a witcher at Kaer Morhen - the stronghold of the witchers. Geralt survived mutations during the Trial of the Grasses, thanks to which he gained various witcher traits: high resistance to injury, poison and disease, slowed ageing, but also infertility. He resisted the \"changes\" brought on by the Trial of Grasses better than most, which encouraged his makers to perform even more dangerous experimental procedures on him, making him lose all body pigmentation. Because of his pale skin and white hair, he is also known in the Elder Speech as \"Gwynbleidd\" (close to the Welsh translation \"Blaidd Gwyn\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geek.com/television/heres-what-you-should-know-about-geralt-of-rivia-in-netflixs-the-witcher-1814551/|title=Here\u2019s What You Should Know About Geralt of Rivia in Netflix\u2019s \u2018The Witcher\u2019|last=Gemmill|first=Allie|date=December 21, 2019|website=Geek|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref>), the White Wolf. From the arduous training of Witchers, he became a master swordfighter and learnt how to use the Signs, simple spells used by the witchers.\n\nDespite his name, Geralt does not come from [[The Witcher#Setting|Rivia]] (although he learned how to mimic a Rivian [[Accent (sociolinguistics)|accent]] and is later knighted for services to the queen of Rivia): young witchers were encouraged to make up surnames for themselves by master Vesemir, to make their names sound more trustworthy. He once claimed that his first choice was Geralt Roger Eric du Haute-Bellegarde, but this was dismissed by Vesemir as silly and pretentious.\n\nAfter completing his witcher training, he received his Wolf medallion (the symbol of Kaer Morhen) and embarked into the world on his horse called ''P\u0142otka'' (literally, \"[[Common roach|Roach]]\" with a diminutive suffix, more accurately \"Roachie\" in English; he gave the same name to every horse he owned) to become a monster slayer for hire.\n\n{{Quote|text=I looked for the words \"Witcher urgently needed\". And then there'd be a sacred site, a dungeon, necropolis or ruins, forest ravine or grotto hidden in the mountains, full of bones and stinking carcasses. Some creatures which lived to kill, out of hunger, for pleasure, or invoked by some sick will. A manticore, wyvern, fogler, aeschna, ilyocoris, chimera, leshy, vampire, ghoul, graveir, were-wolf, giant scorpion, striga, black annis, kikimora, vypper... so many I've killed.|character=Geralt|author=[[Andrzej Sapkowski]]|title=''[[The Last Wish (book)|The Last Wish]]''|source=\"The Voice of Reason 4\"}}\n\nEven though Geralt did not believe in destiny, he unknowingly demanded the unborn child of princess Pavetta and her husband Duny as a reward for his services by invoking \"the Law of Surprise\". The child turned out to be a girl, [[Ciri (character)|Cirilla]], commonly known as Ciri; since then the two are linked to each other. At first, Geralt did not take her because women cannot become witchers. However, fate caused Geralt and Ciri to cross their paths thrice, with him claiming her for a second time when he invokes the Law of Surprise on a traveling merchant he saves from monsters during a random encounter; and after the death of her grandmother, Queen Calanthe of Cintra, Geralt ends up taking the girl into his care, training and loving her as his own daughter. \n\nFollowing the short stories, the novels unfold as Geralt is pulled into a whirlwind of events in his attempts to protect Ciri from those who would do her harm, becoming reluctantly embroiled in the political contentions of monarchs and emperors.\n\n==Literary analysis and reception ==\nGeralt is described as being emblematic of Polish popular culture's spirit of \"[[neo-liberal]] anti-politics\" in the 1990s.<ref name=\"Apor2008\">{{cite book|last=Apor|first=P\u00e9ter|title=Past for the eyes: East European representations of communism in cinema and museums after 1989|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SO8LAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=28 May 2011|year=2008|publisher=Central European University Press|isbn=9789639776050|page=198}}</ref> He is a professional, carrying out his duties and unwilling to become involved in the \"petty quarrels\" of the contemporary politics.<ref name=\"Apor2008\"/> [[Marek Oramus]] compared Geralt to [[Raymond Chandler]]'s signature character [[Philip Marlowe]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Oramus |first=Marek |author-link=Marek Oramus |date=2 September 2000 |title=Only the right image of a witcher |trans-title=Jedynie s\u0142uszny wizerunek wied\u017amina |url=https://archiwum.polityka.pl/art/jedynie-sluszny-wizerunek-wiedzmina,365834.html |language=Polish |work=[[Polityka]] |location=[[Poland]] |access-date=30 May 2011 |pages=52\u201354}}</ref> In 2018, [[GamesRadar]] ranked him as the 6th best hero in video game history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/heroes-in-video-games/3/ |title=The best heroes in video games |last= |first= |date=28 February 2018 |website=[[GamesRadar+]] |publisher=[[Future plc|Future Publishing]] |access-date=31 October 2018 |quote=}}</ref> In 2018, Geralt was included in [[Tom's Guide]] Top 25 Best Video Game Characters of All Time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tomsguide.com/us/pictures-story/1544-best-video-game-characters-of-all-time.html|title=The 25 Best Video Game Characters of All Time|last=July 2018|first=Tom's Guide Staff 07|website=Tom's Guide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==In other media==\n=== Film ===\n[[Micha\u0142 \u017bebrowski]] portrays Geralt in the Polish-language adaptation movie ''[[The Hexer (film)|The Hexer]]''.\n\n===Television===\n* [[Micha\u0142 \u017bebrowski]] portrays Geralt in the polish adaptation series ''[[The Hexer (TV series)|The Hexer]]''.\n* [[Henry Cavill]] portrays Geralt in the [[Netflix]] [[The Witcher (TV series)|adaptation of the books]], the first season of which was released in 2019.<ref name=\"directors\">{{cite web | url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/netflixs-the-witcher-casts-pivotal-roles-of-ciri-yennefer | title=Netflix\u2019S The Witcher casts pivotal roles of Ciri & Yennefer | date=10 October 2018 | publisher=Netflix | accessdate=16 January 2019 }}</ref> Sapkowski served as a creative consultant on the project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/witcher-saga-tv-series-adaptation-ordered-at-netflix-1004558|title='The Witcher' Saga TV Series Adaptation Ordered at Netflix|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Geralt of Rivia.png|thumb|Geralt as he appears in ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]'' (2015)]] -->[[File:W3 SS Geralt.png|thumb|208x208px|Geralt in ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]'']]\nGeralt's adventures continues in a non-canonical version by CD Projekt Red's video game trilogy (''[[The Witcher (video game)|The Witcher]]'', ''[[The Witcher 2: Assassins of Kings]]'' and ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]''), where he is still alive after being killed by a mob during an anti non-human riot at the end of the Witcher novel saga and his body was taken in a boat by his daughter Ciri to [[Avalon]].\n\nSapkowski stated that the games are a work of art of their own and that they cannot be considered either an \"alternative version\", or a sequel, \"because this can only be told by Geralt's creator. A certain Andrzej Sapkowski.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-11-06-ever-wondered-what-the-author-of-the-witcher-books-thinks-about-the-games|title=Ever wondered what the author of The Witcher books thinks about the games?|last=Purchese|first=Robert|date=7 November 2012|work=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nGeralt, voiced by [[Doug Cockle]], appeared as a guest character in the 2018 game ''[[Soulcalibur VI]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.cdprojektred.com/news/play-as-geralt-of-rivia-in-soulcalibur-vi/ |title=Play as Geralt of Rivia in SOULCALIBUR VI! |last= |first= |date=15 March 2018 |website=[[CD Projekt|CD Projekt Red]] |publisher=[[CD Projekt]] |access-date=19 March 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nGeralt also appeared in special content for ''[[Monster Hunter: World]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2019/02/08/monster-hunter-world-the-witcher-ciri-geralt/|title=Monster Hunter World x The Witcher contracts earn you Geralt and Ciri armor and weapon sets|last=Nunneley|first=Stephany|date=February 8, 2019|work=[[VG247]]|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> and ''[[Daemon X Machina]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dualshockers.com/daemon-x-machina-witcher-3-geralt-ciri-dlc/|title=Daemon X Machina Meets The Witcher 3 With New Geralt and Ciri DLC|date=2019-12-05|website=DualShockers|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Novels}}\n*[[Reynevan]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Witcher series}}\n{{Soul series}}\n\n[[Category:The Witcher]]\n[[Category:Characters in fantasy novel series]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video game characters]]\n[[Category:Fantasy film characters]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1986]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who use magic]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with accelerated healing]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with albinism]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with superhuman strength]]\n[[Category:Fictional knights]]\n[[Category:Fictional mutants]]\n[[Category:Fictional monster hunters]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Soulcalibur series guest characters]]\n", "name_user": "142.197.226.197", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geralt_of_Rivia"}
{"title_page": "Nova Scotia killings", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique, Nova Scotia\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.4015|-63.6977}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = Portapique, NS\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n|      label2      = Enfield, Nova Scotia\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title2       = Enfield, NS\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass shooting]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[arson]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 19 (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| injuries         = At least 2<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nOn April 18 and April 19, 2020, Gabriel Wortman shot and killed at least 18 people and set fire to at least five buildings in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]] before being killed by the police following a vehicle pursuit.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nAt 11:32 p.m. on April 18,<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> police responded to multiple [[9-1-1]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\"/><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> They found several dead and injured inside and outside of a home, but no suspect.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The investigation overnight led police to multiple separate crime scenes that were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> By the morning of April 19, police announced that they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. Two residents and a neighbour were later confirmed to be victims. Another victim was then allegedly shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road between Wentworth and Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nResidents were advised by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) to stay indoors, while a portion of Portapique was evacuated.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|publisher=MassLive|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was identified as the shooter at 8:54 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Between 10:04 and 11:24, he was seen in or near [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], and [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref> During this time, police warned that he was [[police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer and operating a replica RCMP vehicle]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline of what we know about Nova Scotia killing spree that left RCMP officer, 16 others dead|publisher=Global News|last=Shah|first=Maryam|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|last=Lopez-Martinez|first=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The public was urged to avoid these areas,<ref name=global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s>{{Cite news|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|last=Quon|first=Alexander|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and to call 9-1-1 immediately if they spotted the fake RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"ABC\" /> An hour later, officials said that Wortman had switched to a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[sports utility vehicle]] (SUV).<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAround this time, the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]] was named as the site of a \"serious criminal event.\"<ref name=\"CBC\" /> A resident of the community reported that they saw two burning vehicles along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2]], including at least one police car, and that they heard an exchange of gunfire between an RCMP officer and a man who ran toward them.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Officials later said this was where Wortman shot and killed RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, and that one of the burning cars was Wortman's replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNearly 12 hours after police first received the firearms complaint,<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|last=Collins|first=Sean|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was killed by police outside an [[Irving Oil]] gas station restaurant in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Investigation==\nNo motive has been established for the killings, and it is not considered by police to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nBy the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires. He said he expected the death toll to continue to rise as these crime scenes were investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\n[[Nova Scotia]]'s [[Serious Incident Response Team]] (SIRT) announced it would coduct an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, as well as a second police use-of-force incident.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/sirt-investigate-discharge-firearm-rcmp-officers|title=SIRT TO INVESTIGATE DISCHARGE OF FIREARM BY RCMP OFFICERS|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were raised about why Nova Scotia did not use its [[emergency alert system]] to warn the public about the killings. The RCMP used Twitter to provide updates, but the areas affected had poor Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not use social media. Usage of Nova Scotia's emergency alert system would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors. Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process to alert the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|publisher=CBC News|last=Gorman|first=Michael|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nAt least 18 people were killed (excluding Wortman), one of them RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, a 23-year veteran. A second RCMP officer was injured and is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC3\"/><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\" /> At least one other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of the first victims had connections to Wortman, but as the killings continued, the targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The victims are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> The RCMP expects to find more victims within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref name=\"CTV4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|first=Meredith|last=MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified Gabriel Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area, on April 19 after he was dead. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> A resident described him as a polite man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman was shown to have had a degree of obsession for policing, with a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with [[alcohol use]] and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Flags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|publisher=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing| website=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=http://archive.is/7qFSQ| archive-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]]\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique, Nova Scotia\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.4015|-63.6977}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = Portapique, NS\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n|      label2      = Enfield, Nova Scotia\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title2       = Enfield, NS\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass shooting]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[arson]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 19 (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| injuries         = At least 2<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nOn April 18 and April 19, 2020, Gabriel Wortman shot and killed at least 18 people and set fire to at least five buildings in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]] before being killed by the police following a vehicle pursuit.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nAt 11:32 p.m. on April 18,<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> police responded to multiple [[9-1-1]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\"/><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> They found several dead and injured inside and outside of a home, but no suspect.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The investigation overnight led police to multiple separate crime scenes that were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> By the morning of April 19, police announced that they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. Two residents and a neighbour were later confirmed to be victims. Another victim was then allegedly shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road between Wentworth and Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nResidents were advised by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) to stay indoors, while a portion of Portapique was evacuated.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|publisher=MassLive|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was identified as the shooter at 8:54 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Between 10:04 and 11:24, he was seen in or near [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], and [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref> During this time, police warned that he was [[police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer and operating a replica RCMP vehicle]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline of what we know about Nova Scotia killing spree that left RCMP officer, 16 others dead|publisher=Global News|last=Shah|first=Maryam|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|last=Lopez-Martinez|first=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The public was urged to avoid these areas,<ref name=global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s>{{Cite news|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|last=Quon|first=Alexander|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and to call 9-1-1 immediately if they spotted the fake RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"ABC\" /> An hour later, officials said that Wortman had switched to a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[sports utility vehicle]] (SUV).<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAround this time, the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]] was named as the site of a \"serious criminal event.\"<ref name=\"CBC\" /> A resident of the community reported that they saw two burning vehicles along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2]], including at least one police car, and that they heard an exchange of gunfire between an RCMP officer and a man who ran toward them.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Officials later said this was where Wortman shot and killed RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, and that one of the burning cars was Wortman's replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNearly 12 hours after police first received the firearms complaint,<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|last=Collins|first=Sean|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was killed by police outside an [[Irving Oil]] gas station restaurant in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Investigation==\nNo motive has been established for the killings, and it is not considered by police to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nBy the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires. He said he expected the death toll to continue to rise as these crime scenes were investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\n[[Nova Scotia]]'s [[Serious Incident Response Team]] (SIRT) announced it would be conducting an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, as well as a second police use-of-force incident.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/sirt-investigate-discharge-firearm-rcmp-officers|title=SIRT TO INVESTIGATE DISCHARGE OF FIREARM BY RCMP OFFICERS|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were raised about why Nova Scotia didn't use its [[emergency alert system]] to warn the public about the killings. The RCMP used Twitter to provide updates, but the areas affected had poor Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not use social media. Usage of Nova Scotia's emergency alert system would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors. Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process to alert the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|publisher=CBC News|last=Gorman|first=Michael|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nAt least 18 people were killed (excluding Wortman), one of them RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, a 23-year veteran. A second RCMP officer was injured and is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC3\"/><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\" /> At least one other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of the first victims had connections to Wortman, but as the killings continued, the targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The victims are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> The RCMP expects to find more victims within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref name=\"CTV4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|first=Meredith|last=MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified Gabriel Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area, on April 19 after he was dead. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> A resident described him as a polite man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman was shown to have had a degree of obsession for policing, with a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with [[alcohol use]] and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Flags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|publisher=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing| website=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=http://archive.is/7qFSQ| archive-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]]\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "InedibleHulk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInvestigation:Syntax.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
{"title_page": "List of people from Prince Albert", "text_new": "This is a list of notable people who are from [[Prince Albert, Saskatchewan]] whether born, raised, or have spent a large part or formative part of their life and or career in that city. Colloquially known as Prince Albertans.\n\n<!--NOTE To EVERYONE!! Make sure that the person you're adding is considered notable. If they have a wikipedia article, then the answer is probably yes. Please also add citations Wikipedia:Citation templates for everyone listed here. DO ''not'' ADD YOURSELF TO THIS LIST-->\n\n{{Compact ToC|seealso=yes|refs=yes}}\n\n==Prince Albertans==\n\n===A===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- align=left\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Occupation\n! style=\"width:60%;\"|Notes\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Ref\n|- \n|[[Sherry Anderson]]||Curler||Canadian and World Senior Curling Champion and has captured silve and bronze at the [[Scotties Tournament of Hearts]].||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcurl.com/player.php?playerid=1505|title=Sherry Anderson|publisher=[[World Curling Tour]] - Powered by CurlingZone|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===B===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- align=left\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Occupation\n! style=\"width:60%;\"|Notes\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Ref\n|- \n|[[Mike Bales]]||Hockey player||[[National Hockey League|NHL]] goalie for the [[Boston Bruins]] and [[Ottawa Senators]]||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=182|title=Mike Bales Hockey Stats and Profile at hockeydb.com|publisher=HockeyDB.com|website=hockeydb.com|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[The Deep Dark Woods|Burke Barlow]]||Musician||Guitarist for the folk band [[The Deep Dark Woods]] from 2005 to 2012||<ref name=deepdarkwods>{{Cite news|url=https://www.okotokstoday.ca/entertainment-news/deep-dark-woods-grows-into-bragg-creek-1525823|title=Deep Dark Woods grows into Bragg Creek|last=Rollie|first=Tammy|date=October 24, 2012|publisher=Okotoks Today|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Scott Basiuk]]||Hockey player||Has played in minor pro hockey leagues in Canada and United States such as [[American Hockey League]] and [[ECHL]].  He most recently played for the [[Sheffield Steelers]] in the [[Elite Ice Hockey League]].||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=54890|title=Scott Basiuk Hockey Stats and Profile at hockeydb.com|publisher=HockeyDB.com|website=hockeydb.com|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Brad Bergen]]||Hockey player||Played his entire career in various leagues in Germany.  He most recently played for [[Schwenninger Wild Wings|SERC Wild Wings]] while they were in [[2nd Bundesliga]].||<ref>{{Cite web||url=https://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=30608|title=Brad Bergen Hockey Stats and Profile at hockeydb.com|publisher=HockeyDB.com|website=hockeydb.com|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Todd Bergen]]||Hockey player||Retired NHL player who played one season with the [[Philadelphia Flyers]] in 1984\u201385||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=342|title=Todd Bergen Hockey Stats and Profile at hockeydb.com|publisher=HockeyDB.com|website=hockeydb.com|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Sheldon Bergstrom]]||Actor||Has done acting in TV, film, and stage.  He does minor roles and is known for ''Rob Ford: The Musical''||<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.macleans.ca/news/canada/the-perfect-rob-ford-a-hired-actor-from-prince-albert/|title=The perfect Rob Ford? A hired actor from Prince Albert|work=[[Canadian Press]]|date=August 5, 2014|publisher=[[Maclean's]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|- \n|[[Mike Botha]]||Master diamond cutter|| World-renowned master diamond cutter and educator known for cutting the Baby Rose, part of the [[Premier Rose Diamond]] and the [[Esperanza Diamond]]; creator of the Sirius Star range of diamond shapes||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://saskatchewanderer.ca/blog/the-worlds-brightest-diamonds-cut-in-saskatchewan|title=The World's Brightest Diamonds Cut in Saskatchewan|date=October 10, 2015|publisher=Saskatchewanderer|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[David Luther Burgess]]||World War I pilot and politician||  World War I [[flying ace]]; in 1926 was the sole challenger to [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] Prime Minister [[William Lyon Mackenzie King]] in a by-election held in Prince Albert; ran as an Independent||<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theaerodrome.com/aces/canada/burgess.php|title=David Luther Burgess|publisher=The Aerodome|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Johnny Bower]]||Hockey player||[[National Hockey League|NHL]] Hall of Famer||<ref>{{cite web| title =Johnny Bower (1953\u201370) | publisher=Hockey Goalies| date =  | url = http://www.hockeygoalies.org/bio/bower.html| accessdate =March 16, 2008}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Robert Boyer (artist)|Robert Boyer]]||Visual artist and professor||M\u00e9tis Cree visual artist and university professor.  His abstract art was known for being politically charged.||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/robert-boyer|title=Robert Boyer|publisher=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[John Ernest Bradshaw]]||Businessman and politician||Opened a general store in 1900 and an insurance business, he Bradshaw Agencies.  He served as Alderman of the city of Prince Albert from 1895 to 1905 and was mayor in 1906.  He represented [[Prince Albert City]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia]] from 1908 to 1917 as a [[Provincial Rights Party]] and then [[Progressive Conservative Party of Saskatchewan|Conservative]] member.||<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio.php?id_nbr=7238|title=Biography - Bradshaw, John Ernest - Volume XIV (1911-1920)|author=David E. Smith|year=1998|work=[[Dictionary of Canadian Biography]]|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===C===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- align=left\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Occupation\n! style=\"width:60%;\"|Notes\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Ref\n|-\n|[[Scotty Cameron (ice hockey)|Scotty Cameron]]||Hockey player||NHL player for the [[New York Rangers]]||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/14318359/angus-cameron|title=Angus \"Scotty\" Cameron (1921-1993)|publisher=Find A Grave|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Allan Casey]]||Author||Born in Regina and raised in Prince Albert; an award nominated author for his non-fiction works||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allancasey.ca/about|title=About|publisher=Allan Casey|website=allancasey.ca|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Deborah Chatsis]]||Ambassador||Born in [[Chilliwack]], [[British Columbia]]; she was raised in Prince Albert and is a member of the [[Ahtahkakoop First Nation]].  Her post-secondary education includes Bachelor's of Science in Mechanical Engineering Bachelor's of Law from the [[University of Saskatchewan]], Masters of Law from the [[University of Ottawa]], Masters in Public Administration from the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] at [[Harvard University]].  Her foreign service career included Ambassador of Canada to Vietnam, Director of South Asia Relations, Ambassador of Canada to Guatemala, High Commissioner to Belize, and [[Global Affairs Canada]].||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.international.gc.ca/gac-amc/podcasts-transcript-balados-transcription-ep17.aspx?lang=eng|title=Transcript \u2013 Episode 17: Chat with Deborah Chatsis|publisher=[[Government of Canada]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Lawrence Clarke (politician)|Lawrence Clarke]]||HBC official and politician||Hudson's Bay Company Official, early Territorial Government Representative and prominent local citizen considered by some to be the instigator of the [[Northwest Rebellion]] of 1885.  He was the first elected [[Member of the Legislative Assembly]]  in [[Northwest Territories]]' history.||<ref>{{cite web | title =LAWRENCE CLARKE: ARCHITECT OF REVOLT | url =https://www.brandonu.ca/Library/CJNS/3.1/shulman.pdf | format =PDF | accessdate =March 16, 2008 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20090327120323/http://www.brandonu.ca/Library/CJNS/3.1/shulman.pdf | archive-date =March 27, 2009 | url-status =dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Don Cody]]||Business owner and politician||He represented [[Watrous (former electoral district)|Watrous]] from 1971 to 1975 and [[Kinistino (Saskatchewan provincial electoral district)|Kinistino]] from 1978 to 1982 in the [[Legislative Assembly of Saskatchewan]] as a [[Saskatchewan New Democratic Party|New Democratic Party]] member.  He was mayor of Prince Albert from 1994-2003.||<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y746xOWGfcUC&pg=PA45 |pages=45\u20136 |title=Saskatchewan Politicians: Lives Past and Present|year=2004|ISBN=0889771650|publisher=Canadian Plains Research Center Press |author=Brett Quiring|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[John Comiskey (Canadian football)|John Comiskey]]||Football player||Played [[Canadian football center|center]] with the [[Calgary Stampeders]] in the [[Canadian Football League|CFL]]||<ref name>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/football/cfl/stampeders-comiskey/|title=Stampeders bring Comiskey back into fold|date=January 26, 2010|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Adam Cracknell]]||Hockey player||While in the [[National Hockey League|NHL]] he played for [[St. Louis Blues]], [[Columbus Blue Jackets]], [[Vancouver Canucks]], [[Edmonton Oilers]], [[Dallas Stars]], [[New York Rangers]], and [[Anaheim Ducks]].  He currently plays for [[Kunlun Red Star]] of the [[Kontinental Hockey League]].||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=68995|title=Adam Cracknell Hockey Stats and Profile at hockeydb.com|publisher=HockeyDB.com|website=hockeydb.com|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|- \n|[[Neil Stanley Crawford]]||Politician and jazz musician||Practised law in [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], in the 1950s and 1960s; served as an executive assistant to Prime Minister John Diefenbaker between 1961 and 1963; served as Young [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] Association President from 1963 to 1964; had a jazz band composed of provincial MLAs called the Tory Blue Notes, in which he played trumpet.||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/118312395/neil-stanley-crawford|title=Neil Stanley Crawford (1931-1992)|publisher=Find A Grave|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[John Marcel Cuelenaere]]||Lawyer and politician||{{Post-nominals|country=CAN|QC}}; He represented [[Shellbrook (electoral district)|Shellbrook]] from 1964 to 1967 in the [[Legislative Assembly of Saskatchewan]] as a [[Saskatchewan Liberal Party|Liberal]].  Was member of the [[Prince Albert City Council|Prince Albert city council]] and served as mayor from 1946 to 1954.||<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y746xOWGfcUC&pg=PA53|title=Saskatchewan Politicians: Lives Past and Present|author=Brett Quiring|ISBN=0889771650|pages=53\u201354|year=2004|publisher=Canadian Plains Research Center Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Ruth Cuthand]]||Artist||An artist who specializes in traditional craft (beadwork), drawing and printmaking.||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ruthcuthand.ca/cv/|title=Ruth Cuthand|publisher=Ruth Cuthand|website=ruthcuthand.ca|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===D===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- align=left\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Occupation\n! style=\"width:60%;\"|Notes\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Ref\n|-\n|[[Rod Dallman]]||Hockey player||NHL player for the [[New York Islanders]] and Philadelphia Flyers; career penalty minute leader for the [[Springfield Indians]]; born in [[Quesnel, British Columbia]], played junior hockey for the [[Prince Albert Raiders]]; currently lives in Prince Albert.||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=1241|title=Rod Dallman Hockey Stats and Profile at hockeydb.com|publisher=HockeyDB.com|website=hockeydb.com|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Scott Daniels (ice hockey)|Scott Daniels]]||Hockey player||Played in the [[National Hockey League|NHL]] for [[Hartford Whalers]], [[Philadelphia Flyers]], and [[New Jersey Devils]].||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/69111/scott-daniels1|title=Scott Daniels|publisher=Elite Prospects|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Ron Davidson]]||Hockey player and lawyer||He played with [[1979\u201380 Canada men's national ice hockey team|Team Canada]] at the [[Ice hockey at the 1980 Winter Olympics|1980 Winter Olympics]].  He graduated from [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] law school in 1982. Following university, he played professional hockey in Sweden, Switzerland, and France for four years before starting his law career in 1986 in Ottawa.  He remained active in hockey as assistant at Howie Meeker's hockey schools and later as director of hockey programming for the [[Ottawa Senators]].||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/2825/ron-davidson|title=Ron Davidson|publisher=Elite Prospects|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.willdavidson.ca/team/ron-davidson/|title=Ron Davidson - Counsel|publisher=Will Davidson LLP|website=willdavidson.ca|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Thomas Clayton Davis]]||Lawyer, judge, diplomat, and politician||Son of Thomas Osborne Davis; he practised law in Prince Albert and later served two terms as alderman for the city; he was mayor from 1921 to 1924.  He represented [[Prince Albert City|Prince Albert]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of Saskatchewan]] from 1925 to 1939 as a [[Saskatchewan Liberal Party|Liberal]].||<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sasklawcourts.ca/default.asp?pg=ca_justices_21|title=The Honourable Thomas Clayton Davis|publisher=Courts of Saskatchewan |accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051227145714/http://www.sasklawcourts.ca/default.asp?pg=ca_justices_21 |archivedate=December 27, 2005}}</ref> \n|-\n|[[Thomas Osborne Davis (Canadian politician)|Thomas Osborne Davis]]||Politician||Father of Thomas Clayton Davis.  Liberal Member of Parliament in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] representing the [[Provisional District of Saskatchewan]], and later a member of the [[Senate of Canada]]; served on the town council for Prince Albert; mayor from 1894 to 1895; died in office as mayor when he was 60\n|-\n|[[Guy Delparte]]||Hockey player||Played in 48 [[National Hockey League|NHL]] games with the [[Colorado Rockies (NHL)|Colorado Rockies]] during the [[1976\u201377 NHL season|1976\u201377 season]].||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/114059/guy-delparte|title=Guy Delparte|publisher=Elite Prospects|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Ivor Dent]]||Politician||{{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}}; born in Prince Albert; became a politician in Alberta; former mayor of Edmonton; former candidate for the House of Commons of Canada and the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]]||<ref name=\"Dent, Ivor G.\">{{cite web|url=http://www.epl.ca/Elections/Results/EPLBiographies/D.cfm#5 |title=Dent, Ivor G. |publisher=Edmonton Public Library |accessdate=2009-04-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080117194729/http://www.epl.ca/Elections/results/EPLBiographies/D.cfm |archivedate=January 17, 2008 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Selwyn Dewdney]]||Author, illustrator, artist, activist and pioneer in both art therapy and pictography||Born in Prince Albert, moved to [[Kenora]], [[Ontario]]; received post-secondary education at the [[University of Toronto]] where he received a general Bachelor of Arts; [[Ontario College of Education]]; received a High School Assistant's Certificate and Art Specialists Certificate.||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.morebooks.de/store/gb/book/selwyn-dewdney/isbn/978-613-8-66719-3|title=Selwayn Dewdney|publisher=More Books|website=morebooks.de|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Don Dickinson]]||Writer and author||Award winning writer and author.  His post-secondary education included being a graduate of [[University of Saskatchewan]] and [[University of British Columbia]].  He was nominated and shortlisted for a number of awards including winning the [[Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]] in 1992 for ''Blue Husbands''.||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcbookworld.com/writer/dickinson-don/|title=Don Dickinson|publisher=ABC Bookworld|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[John Diefenbaker]]||[[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]]||(1895-1979) [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|PC]], [[Order of the Companions of Honour|CH]], [[Queen's Counsel|QC]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Canada|FRSC]], [[Royal Society of Arts|FRSA]]; 13th Prime Minister of Canada, serving 1957-1963; [[Diefenbaker House]] in Prince Albert is open as a museum to the public in the summer season, the home where Diefenbaker lived for ten years with his first wife, [[Edna Brower]] and when she died, his second, [[Olive Diefenbaker|Olive Palmer]]||<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.ca/primeministers/h4-3330-e.html|title=ARCHIVED - Diefenbaker-Facts-First Among Equals|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|website=collectionscanada.ca|date=April 23, 2001|accessdate=December 10, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Samuel James Donaldson]]||Farmer, rancher, police officer, and politician||He served on the council for Prince Albert from 1889 to 1908 and was mayor from 1892 to 1894.   He represented Prince Albert County and then [[Shellbrook (electoral district)|Shellbrook]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of Saskatchewan]] from 1905 to 1915 as a [[Provincial Rights Party|Provincial Rights]]-[[Saskatchewan Progressive Conservative Party|Conservative]] [[