ympic.ca|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Victoria Jurgens]]||Politician||Represented the [[Saskatchewan Party]] from 2011-2016 in the [[Prince Albert Northcote]] riding.||<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://panow.com/2019/05/28/former-mla-seeks-local-sask-party-nomination/|title=Former MLA seeks local Sask. Party nomination|last=Maxwell|first=Nigel|date=May 28, 2019|publisher=PANow|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===K===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- align=left\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Occupation\n! style=\"width:60%;\"|Notes\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Ref\n|-\n|[[Marliese Kasner]]||Curler and teacher||[[2003 World Junior Curling Championships|2003]] World Junior Champion and former member of her sister [[Stefanie Lawton]]'s team.||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcurl.com/player.php?playerid=612|title=Marliese Kasner|publisher=[[World Curling Tour]] - Powered by CurlingZone|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Boris Karloff]]||Actor||Known for his roles in horror films portraying characters like [[Frankenstein]]'s Monster and [[The Mummy (1932 film)|The Mummy]]; resided in Prince Albert during the early 20th century; applied to Harry St. Clair of Prince Albert's Harry St. Clair players and toured with them between 1912 and 1914 before becoming famous in Hollywood||<ref>{{cite web | title = Tourism Prince Albert&nbsp;\u2014 Our Proud History | url = http://www.patourism.ca/history.aspx | accessdate =March 16, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080304065407/http://www.patourism.ca/history.aspx <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = March 4, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jacobs |first=Stephen |title=Boris Karloff in Alberta |year=2007 |url=http://www.morethanamonster.com/Boris%20Karloff%20in%20Alberta.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=May 22, 2009|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714114432/http://www.morethanamonster.com/Boris%20Karloff%20in%20Alberta.pdf |archivedate=July 14, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last = Buehrer | first =Beverley Bare  | title = Boris Karloff By  | publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group | year = 1993 | location = |isbn=9780313277153 |format= published on line by Google books | page = 5 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=nmd77kTyX_oC&pg=PA5&lpg=PA5&dq=%22Boris+Karloff%22++%22Prince+Albert%22 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Andrew Knox (Canadian politician)|Andrew Knox]]||Politican and farmer||He represented [[Prince Albert (electoral district)|Prince Albert]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] from 1917 to 1925. He was elected to Parliament in the [[1917 Canadian federal election|1917 federal election]] as a [[Liberal-Unionist]] supporter of Sir [[Robert Borden]]'s wartime [[Unionist Party (Canada)|Union Government]]. After the war, he [[crossed the floor]] to join the new [[Progressive Party of Canada|Progressive Party]].||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lop.parl.ca/sites/ParlInfo/default/en_CA/People/Profile?personId=10414|title=Profile <nowiki>|</nowiki> Knox, Andrew|publisher=Parlinfo - Parliament of Canada|website=parl.ca|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Kirk Krack]]||Freediver||Broke records throughout his career; created Performance Freediving International, Canadian Association of Freediving and Apnea; founding member of the United States Apnea Association; organized many competitions; head safety for the Cayman Challenge; has done film and TV work associated with freediving||<ref>{{cite web| title = Kirk Krack bio| publisher = Performance Freediving International| url = http://www.performancefreediving.com/team-bios/kirk-krack/| doi = | accessdate = August 9, 2015| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150904003808/http://www.performancefreediving.com/team-bios/kirk-krack/| archive-date = September 4, 2015| url-status = dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Jason Krywulak]]||Hockey player||Played three games for the [[San Diego Gulls]] in the minor pro [[West Coast Hockey League]] during the [[1997\u201398 WCHL season|1997\u201398]] season before returning to the [[University of Calgary]].  From 1998-2000, he played the rest of career in Germany.||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=2842|title=Jason Krywulak Stats and Profile at hockeydb.com|publisher=HockeyDB.com|website=hockeydb.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Orland Kurtenbach]]||Hockey player||During his career in the [[National Hockey League|NHL]], he played for the [[Vancouver Canucks]], [[New York Rangers]], [[Toronto Maple Leafs]], and [[Boston Bruins]].  He was the Canucks' inaugural captain||<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sasksportshalloffame.com/inductees/orland-kurtenbach/|title=Orland Kurtenbach|publisher=Saskatchewan Sports Hall of Fame|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===L===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- align=left\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Occupation\n! style=\"width:60%;\"|Notes\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Ref\n|-\n|[[John Henderson Lamont]]||Supreme Court Justice||Born in Horning's Mills, [[Canada West]]; became a Prince Albert lawyer, Liberal politician, and Supreme Court Justice||<ref>{{cite web|title=Supreme Court of Canada&nbsp;\u2014 John Henderson Lamont |date=January 6, 2009 |url=http://www.scc-csc.gc.ca/court-cour/ju/lamont/index-eng.asp |accessdate=May 23, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614153702/http://www.scc-csc.gc.ca/court-cour/ju/lamont/index-eng.asp |archivedate=June 14, 2011 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Stefanie Lawton]]||Curler||[[Marliese Kasner]]'s sister and former teammate.  [[2000 Canadian Junior Curling Championships|2000]] Canadian Junior Champion.||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcurl.com/player.php?playerid=12019|title=Stefanie Lawton|publisher=[[World Curling Tour]] - Powered by CurlingZone|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Bob Lowes]]||Ice hockey coach and executive||Two-time winner of the Canadian Hockey League Coach of the Year Award||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/161403/bob-lowes|title=Bob Lowes|publisher=Elite Prospects|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===M===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- align=left\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Occupation\n! style=\"width:60%;\"|Notes\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Ref\n|-\n|[[Charles Mair]] ||Poet||19th-century Canadian nationalist poet who resided in Prince Albert for several years in the early 1880s||<ref>{{Cite book | last = Mair | first = Charles | authorlink = David Leonard, Brian Calliou, Historical Society of Alberta.  | title = Through the Mackenzie Basin  | publisher=[[University of Alberta]] | year = 1999 | pages = XXV | url = https://books.google.com/?id=gLtfcrqBd2YC&pg=PP27&lpg=PP27&dq=%22Charles+Mair%22++%22Prince+Albert%22 | isbn =9780888643261 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Day Hort MacDowall]]||Politician||Prominent citizen; elected as an MLA representing Prince Albert in the [[Legislative Assembly of Northwest Territories]] in 1883 and served until 1885||<ref>{{cite web | title = PARLINFO&nbsp;\u2014 Parliamentarian File&nbsp;\u2014 Federal Experience&nbsp;\u2014 MACDOWALL, Day Hort |work=Library of Parliament | publisher=Government of Canada | url =http://www2.parl.gc.ca/Parlinfo/Files/Parliamentarian.aspx?Item=a956d6f0-b2b4-477f-a37e-3e7d8acef076&Language=E | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20110604065447/http://www.parl.gc.ca/parlinfo/Files/Parliamentarian.aspx?Item=a956d6f0-b2b4-477f-a37e-3e7d8acef076&Language=E | url-status =dead | archive-date =June 4, 2011 | accessdate =May 22, 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[The Deep Dark Woods|Chris Mason]]||Musician||Former bassist for the folk rock band [[The Deep Dark Woods]]||<ref name=deepdarkwods/>\n|-\n|[[Dave Manson]]||Hockey player||Retired NHL player who started out with the [[Chicago Blackhawks]]; now an assistant coach with his former junior hockey team, WHL's Prince Albert Raiders\n|<ref>{{cite web | title = Legends of Hockey \u2013 NHL Player Search \u2013 Player \u2013 Dave Manson | publis