bout Anne's creator]. The Globe and Mail. Retrieved September 20, 2008. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308031240/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20080919.wmhmontgomery0920/BNStory/mentalhealth |date=March 8, 2009 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Blair Morgan]]||Motocross/snowcross athlete||Five-time X-Games gold medalist for snowcross||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://snoriderswest.com/article/rideon/blair_morgan_i_never_thought_id_be_racing_again|title=Blair Morgan: \"I never thought I\u2019d be racing again\"|last=Armleder|first=Kirsten|date=February 28, 2018|publisher=Snoriders|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Jerome Mrazek]]||Hockey player||[[Canadian]] retired professional [[ice hockey]] [[goaltender]] who played in [[List of players who played only one game in the NHL|one NHL game]] for the Philadelphia Flyers\n|<ref>{{cite web | title = Legends of Hockey \u2013 NHL Player Search \u2013 Player \u2013 Jerome Mrazek | publisher = Hockey Hall of Fame and Museum | date = 2001\u20132008 | url = http://www.legendsofhockey.net:8080/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=18637 | accessdate = May 22, 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071113182742/http://www.legendsofhockey.net:8080/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=18637 | archive-date = November 13, 2007 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Wynona Mulcaster]]||Artist, teacher, and competitive riding instructor||She obtained a BA in Art and English from the [[University of Saskatchewan]], sudied art at the [[Banff Centre for Arts and Creativity]] and  Montreal Museum of Fine Arts School of Art and Design.  As an artist she painted prairie landscapes, which show the form and vitality of the land and the sky.  In 1993 she was given the Lifetime Award for Excellence in the Arts by the [[Saskatchewan Arts Board]].  As a teacher she helped established what became the [[Emma Lake Artist's Workshops]], taught at [[Saskatchewan Teachers' College]] in 1943 serving as Director of Art Education from 1945 to 1948.  Between 1964 and 1977, she was Associate Professor in the Department of Visual Art at the University of Saskatchewan.  From 1943 to 1977, she was the instructor at the Saskatoon [[Pony Club]].  She trained many riders who went onto medal at various international competitions including the Olympics, Pan-American Games, and World Championships.  Was inducted into the Saskatoon Sports Hall of Fame in 1994.||<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gallerieswest.ca/news/noted-saskatchewan-artist-wynona-mulcaster-dies-in-mexico-at/|title=Noted Saskatchewan artist Wynona Mulcaster dies in Mexico at age 101|author=[[Remai Modern]]|date=September 7, 2016|publisher=Galleries West|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Lloyd John Muller]]||Politician and farmer||Represented the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Saskatchewan|Progressive Conservative]] as an MLA in the [[Shellbrook (electoral district)|Shellbrok-Torch River]] riding from 1982-1991.||\n|}\n\n===N===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- align=left\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Occupation\n! style=\"width:60%;\"|Notes\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Ref\n|-\n|[[Jeff Nelson (ice hockey)|Jeff Nelson]]||Hockey player||Played in the NHL for the [[Washington Capitals]] and [[Nashville Predators]].||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=3939|title=Jeff Nelson [ca. 1988-2011] Hockey Stats and Profile at hockeydb.com|publisher=HockeyDB.com|website=hockeydb.com|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Ted Newall]]||Entrepreneur||{{Post-nominals|country=CAN|OC}}; received post-secondary education at the [[University of Saskatchewan]].  He served as, chairman, vice-president and CEO of DuPont Canada Inc.; vice-chairman and CEO of NOVA Corporation.  Was chairman in various other companies and corporations.  Was a [[University of Calgary]] board member.||<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.macleans.ca/article/1996/12/23/ted-newall|titl