olk rock band [[The Deep Dark Woods]]||<ref name=deepdarkwods/>\n|-\n|[[Dave Manson]]||Hockey player||Retired NHL player who started out with the [[Chicago Blackhawks]]; now an assistant coach with his former junior hockey team, WHL's Prince Albert Raiders\n|<ref>{{cite web | title = Legends of Hockey \u2013 NHL Player Search \u2013 Player \u2013 Dave Manson | publisher = Hockey Hall of Fame and Museum| url = http://www.legendsofhockey.net:8080/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=11017 | accessdate = May 25, 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081211173639/http://www.legendsofhockey.net:8080/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=11017 | archive-date = December 11, 2008| url-status = dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[John Paul Meagher]]||Politician and developer||Represented the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Saskatchewan|Progressive Conservatives]] in Prince Albert riding from 1982-1986.||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thestarphoenix.remembering.ca/obituary/john-paul-meagher-1074884290|title=John Paul Meagher <nowiki>|</nowiki> Obituary|publisher=[[Saskatoon StarPhoenix]]||website=remembering.ca|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Tracy Medve]]||Airline executive||Former president of [[Canadian North]]||\n|-\n|[[Thomas McKay (N.W.T. politician)|Thomas McKay]]||Politician and farmer||Represented Prince Albert in the Legislative Assembly of the Northwest Territories, 1891-1894 and 1898-1905; brother-in-law of Lawrence Clarke, and like Clarke was connected to the Conservative Party of Canada; first mayor of Prince Albert; a Protestant M\u00e9tis or Anglo-M\u00e9tis; was involved in the [[Saskatchewan Rebellion]] on the side of the federal government||<ref name=historyofpa/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metismuseum.ca/media/document.php/11390.Thomas%20McKay.pdf|title=Thomas McKay, M.L.A.|last=Rozyk|first=Amanda|date=May 7, 2009|publisher=Louis Riel Institute|website=metismuseum.ca|format=PDF|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Lucy Maud M