esign.  As an artist she painted prairie landscapes, which show the form and vitality of the land and the sky.  In 1993 she was given the Lifetime Award for Excellence in the Arts by the [[Saskatchewan Arts Board]].  As a teacher she helped established what became the [[Emma Lake Artist's Workshops]], taught at [[Saskatchewan Teachers' College]] in 1943 serving as Director of Art Education from 1945 to 1948.  Between 1964 and 1977, she was Associate Professor in the Department of Visual Art at the University of Saskatchewan.  From 1943 to 1977, she was the instructor at the Saskatoon [[Pony Club]].  She trained many riders who went onto medal at various international competitions including the Olympics, Pan-American Games, and World Championships.  Was inducted into the Saskatoon Sports Hall of Fame in 1994.||<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gallerieswest.ca/news/noted-saskatchewan-artist-wynona-mulcaster-dies-in-mexico-at/|title=Noted Saskatchewan artist Wynona Mulcaster dies in Mexico at age 101|author=[[Remai Modern]]|date=September 7, 2016|publisher=Galleries West|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Lloyd John Muller]]||Politician and farmer||Represented the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Saskatchewan|Progressive Conservative]] as an MLA in the [[Shellbrook (electoral district)|Shellbrok-Torch River]] riding from 1982-1991.||\n|}\n\n===N===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- align=left\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Occupation\n! style=\"width:60%;\"|Notes\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Ref\n|-\n|[[Jeff Nelson (ice hockey)|Jeff Nelson]]||Hockey player||Played in the NHL for the [[Washington Capitals]] and [[Nashville Predators]].||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=3939|title=Jeff Nelson [ca. 1988-2011] Hockey Stats and Profile at hockeydb.com|publisher=HockeyDB.com|website=hockeydb.com|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Ted Newall]]||Entrepreneur||{{Post-nominals|country=CAN|OC}}; received